TITLE: Using error() to Signal Illegal State in Kotlin
DESCRIPTION: This Kotlin code demonstrates using the error() function to indicate an illegal state, specifically within a when expression. If the user's role is not one of the expected values, an IllegalStateException is thrown, signaling that the role is undefined. This approach provides a clear way to handle unexpected cases.
SOURCE: https://github.com/jetbrains/kotlin-web-site/blob/master/docs/topics/exceptions.md#_snippet_4

LANGUAGE: kotlin
CODE:
```
class User(val name: String, val role: String)

fun processUserRole(user: User) {
    when (user.role) {
        "admin" -> println("${user.name} is an admin.")
        "editor" -> println("${user.name} is an editor.")
        "viewer" -> println("${user.name} is a viewer.")
        else -> error("Undefined role: ${user.role}")
    }
}

fun main() {
    // This works as expected
    val user1 = User("Alice", "admin")
    processUserRole(user1)
    // Alice is an admin.

    // This throws an IllegalStateException
    val user2 = User("Bob", "guest")
    processUserRole(user2)
}
```

