TITLE: Handling Nullable Values with Early Returns on Null Checks in Kotlin
DESCRIPTION: This snippet shows an alternative way to handle nullable values returned by `parseInt`. The `printProduct` function checks `x` and `y` individually for null. If a null is found, an error message is printed, and the function returns early. If both checks pass, `x` and `y` are smart-cast to non-nullable `Int` and their product is printed.
SOURCE: https://github.com/jetbrains/kotlin-web-site/blob/master/docs/topics/basic-syntax.md#2025-04-22_snippet_22

LANGUAGE: kotlin
CODE:
```
fun parseInt(str: String): Int? {
    return str.toIntOrNull()
}

fun printProduct(arg1: String, arg2: String) {
    val x = parseInt(arg1)
    val y = parseInt(arg2)

//sampleStart
    // ...
    if (x == null) {
        println("Wrong number format in arg1: '$arg1'")
        return
    }
    if (y == null) {
        println("Wrong number format in arg2: '$arg2'")
        return
    }

    // x and y are automatically cast to non-nullable after null check
    println(x * y)
//sampleEnd
}

fun main() {
    printProduct("6", "7")
    printProduct("a", "7")
    printProduct("99", "b")
}
```

