TITLE: Illustrating Function Mangling with Kotlin Inline Classes
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates the concept of function name mangling for functions accepting inline classes. Because the inline class `UInt` is represented as its underlying type `Int` at runtime, the two `compute` functions would normally have the same JVM signature (`compute(int)`). Kotlin avoids this clash by mangling the name of the function accepting the inline class, appending a hashcode.
SOURCE: https://github.com/jetbrains/kotlin-web-site/blob/master/docs/topics/inline-classes.md#2025-04-22_snippet_7

LANGUAGE: kotlin
CODE:
```
@JvmInline
value class UInt(val x: Int)

// Represented as 'public final void compute(int x)' on the JVM
fun compute(x: Int) { }

// Also represented as 'public final void compute(int x)' on the JVM!
fun compute(x: UInt) { }
```

