TITLE: Floating-Point Number Comparison in Kotlin
DESCRIPTION: This snippet illustrates the differences in behavior when comparing floating-point numbers in Kotlin, particularly with NaN and zero values. It shows how the comparison behavior changes depending on whether operands are statically typed as floating-point numbers.
SOURCE: https://github.com/jetbrains/kotlin-web-site/blob/master/docs/topics/numbers.md#2025-04-22_snippet_14

LANGUAGE: kotlin
CODE:
```
fun main() {
    //sampleStart
    // Operand statically typed as floating-point number
    println(Double.NaN == Double.NaN)                 // false

    // Operand NOT statically typed as floating-point number
    // So NaN is equal to itself
    println(listOf(Double.NaN) == listOf(Double.NaN)) // true

    // Operand statically typed as floating-point number
    println(0.0 == -0.0)                              // true

    // Operand NOT statically typed as floating-point number
    // So -0.0 is less than 0.0
    println(listOf(0.0) == listOf(-0.0))              // false

    println(listOf(Double.NaN, Double.POSITIVE_INFINITY, 0.0, -0.0).sorted())
    // [-0.0, 0.0, Infinity, NaN]
    //sampleEnd
}
```

