TITLE: Delegating Interface Implementation in Kotlin
DESCRIPTION: This Kotlin snippet shows how a class `Derived` can implement an interface `Base` by delegating its public members to an instance of another class `BaseImpl`. The `by` keyword simplifies the delegation, allowing `Derived` to pass method calls to the delegate instance `b`. Dependencies include Kotlin standard library and interface `Base`. Key parameters are `b` which is the delegate instance. Inputs include the integer to `BaseImpl`. Output is the value being printed to standard output.
SOURCE: https://github.com/jetbrains/kotlin-web-site/blob/master/docs/topics/delegation.md#2025-04-22_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: kotlin
CODE:
```
interface Base {
    fun print()
}

class BaseImpl(val x: Int) : Base {
    override fun print() { print(x) }
}

class Derived(b: Base) : Base by b

fun main() {
    val base = BaseImpl(10)
    Derived(base).print()
}
```

